===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ga}} {{term|bean|lang=ga}} {{term|sí|lang=ga}}, from {{etyl|sga}} {{term|ben|lang=sga}} {{term|síde||woman of the fairy mound|lang=sga}}.  The term {{term||banshee}} entered English in 1771.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-banshee.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{IPA|/bænˈʃiː/}} or {{IPAchar|/ˈbænʃiː/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# In Irish [[folklore]], a female [[spirit]], usually taking the form of a woman whose [[mournful]] [[wail]]ing warns of an [[impend]]ing death. Originally a [[fairy]] woman singing a [[caoin|caoineadh]] ([[lament]]) for recently-deceased members of the O’Grady, the O’Neill, the O’Brien, the O’Connor, and the Kavanagh families, translations into English made a distinction between the banshee and other fairy folk that the original language and original stories do not seem to have, and thus the current image of the banshee.

